article.headline: Yale 27, Columbia 12
article.story: NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- Senior running back Mike McLeod rushed for three touchdowns as Yale snapped a two-game losing streak with a 27-12 victory Saturday over error-prone Columbia. Columbia (1-6, 1-3 Ivy League) outgained Yale 316-269, but turned the ball over three times and suffered a blocked punt. McLeod, the Ivy League's most valuable player last season, rushed for 85 yards on 23 carries and caught three passes or 25 yards for Yale (4-3, 2-2). Bothered by a lingering ankle sprain much of the season, McLeod had scored only three touchdowns in the Bulldogs' first six games. McLeod rushed for touchdowns of 8 and 1 yards in the first half, the latter set up by a blocked Columbia punt returned by Yale's Shane Bannon to the Lions' 2-yard line. That gave the Bulldogs a 14-6 halftime lead. Yale defensive lineman Kyle Hawari forced a third-quarter fumble by sacking Columbia quarterback M.A. Olawale deep in his own territory, setting up McLeod's final touchdown, a two-yard run. Columbia scored its only touchdown when backup quarterback Shane Kelly finished an 80-yard drive with a 10-yard run late in the third quarter.
